aws::graph::propositions: # Aviation Accident Information for Shelbyville, Illinois on September 13, 2012
The accident occurred in Shelbyville, Illinois.
The accident occurred on September 13, 2012, at 10:30 Local time.
The aircraft involved was a Bruce M Barrett STOLP STARLET SA500.
The aircraft registration was N935B.
The defining event of the accident was loss of engine power (total).
The flight was conducted under Part 91: General aviation - Personal.
The accident number was CEN12LA632.
The aircraft sustained substantial damage.
The pilot suffered no injuries.
The pilot reported the engine lost power completely and without warning.
The engine lost power approximately 1 hour after takeoff.
The aircraft was established in cruise flight at 3,000 feet mean sea level when the engine lost power.
The pilot's efforts to restore engine power were not successful.
The pilot executed a forced landing to a bean field.
The airplane nosed over during the landing roll.
A postaccident examination of the engine revealed no evidence of an engine malfunction or failure.
Surface weather conditions in the vicinity of the accident site indicated the potential for serious carburetor icing at glide power.
Surface weather conditions in the vicinity of the accident site indicated the potential for moderate icing at cruise power.
The exact weather conditions at cruise altitude were not known.
An abrupt loss of engine power is not consistent with carburetor icing.
The underlying cause of the loss of engine power could not be determined.
The National Transportation Safety Board determined the probable cause of the accident to be an abrupt, complete loss of engine power during cruise flight.
The reasons for the engine power loss could not be determined because postaccident examination did not reveal any anomalies.

text:
# Aviation Investigation Final Report

## Location:
Shelbyville, Illinois

## Date & Time: 
September 13, 2012, 10:30 Local

## Aircraft:
Bruce M Barrett STOLP STARLET SA500

## Defining Event:
Loss of engine power (total)

## Flight Conducted Under:
Part 91: General aviation - Personal

## Accident Number:
CEN12LA632

## Registration:
N935B

## Aircraft Damage:
Substantial

## Injuries:
1 None

## Analysis
The pilot reported that about 1 hour after takeoff, while established in cruise flight at 3,000 feet mean sea level, the engine lost power completely and without warning. His efforts to restore engine power were not successful. He executed a forced landing to a bean field and the airplane nosed over during the landing roll. A postaccident examination of the engine revealed no evidence of an engine malfunction or failure. Surface weather conditions in the vicinity of the accident site indicated the potential for serious carburetor icing at glide power and moderate icing at cruise power. The exact weather conditions at cruise altitude were not known. Further, an abrupt loss of engine power is not consistent with carburetor icing. Accordingly, a determination of the underlying cause of the loss of engine power could not be determined.

## Probable Cause and Findings
The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be: An abrupt, complete loss of engine power during cruise flight for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination of the airframe and engine did not reveal any anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.
